"We don't hate the elephants, but their activities are making us poor," said a 53-year old farmer, surveying his lush green fields, a five-hectare (12-acre) plot on the slopes of the Laikipia highlands in central Kenya.

While poachers slaughter thousands of elephants across Africa each year, competition between elephants and people over land is a far bigger problem in the long run.

